          FacebookYesterday a U.S. federal judge  dismissed two antitrust l=
awsuits against Facebook Inc., brought by the U.S. Federal Trade Commission=
 and a group of state attorneys general,=C2=A0claiming that it has a monopo=
ly on social networking. Facebook investors celebrated by buying its stock =
and pushing its market capitalization above $1 trillion, which is maybe a l=
ittle on the nose? =E2=80=9CWhat, little old us, a=C2=A0monopoly? No, alas,=
=C2=A0we=E2=80=99re just a=C2=A0scrappy little startup=C2=A0doing our best =
to survive in this crazy world,=E2=80=9D Mark Zuckerberg could say, nervous=
ly trying to stand between you and the ticker showing that his company is n=
ow worth a trillion dollars. I dunno, doesn=E2=80=99t a trillion dollars=C2=
=A0sound=C2=A0like a monopoly?Here=E2=80=99s the basic problem with the Fac=
ebook case. To win an antitrust lawsuit, the government has to show that Fa=
cebook has =E2=80=9Cmonopoly power=E2=80=9D in some relevant market. Monopo=
ly power means, specifically, the ability to raise prices above a competiti=
ve level. Here=E2=80=99s how the judge=E2=80=99s opinion puts the question[=
1]:Monopoly power is the =E2=80=9Cthe power to control prices or exclude co=
mpetition,=E2=80=9D such that a firm is a monopolist =E2=80=9Cif it can pro=
fitably raise prices substantially above the competitive level.=E2=80=9D Wh=
ere a plaintiff can provide direct proof that a =E2=80=9Cfirm has in fact p=
rofitably done so, the existence of monopoly power is clear.=E2=80=9D Becau=
se such proof is rare, however, plaintiffs and courts usually search for in=
direct or =E2=80=9Ccircumstantial evidence=E2=80=9D of monopoly power by in=
ferring it from =E2=80=9Ca firm=E2=80=99s possession of a dominant share of=
 a relevant market.=E2=80=9D Because =E2=80=9C[m]arket power is meaningful =
only if it is durable,=E2=80=9D a plaintiff proceeding by the indirect meth=
od of providing a relevant market and share thereof must also show that the=
re are =E2=80=9Cbarriers to entry=E2=80=9D into that market.=C2=A0Fine. Now=
, what is the relevant market? The government argued, and the court accepte=
d, that the market is =E2=80=9CPersonal Social Networking (PSN) Services.=
=E2=80=9D I will not bother discussing the definition of this market becaus=
e you probably get the gist of it. (Facebook objected that this is not a we=
ll-defined market and that =E2=80=9Cit is =E2=80=98obvious that people=E2=
=80=99 also know how to =E2=80=98connect and share with family and friends =
. . . via many [other] technologies,=E2=80=99 such as =E2=80=98email, messa=
ging, photo-sharing, and video-chats,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D but never mind. Fac=
ebook has  previously argued that it is not a monopoly because it competes =
in =E2=80=9Cthe space of people connecting with other people,=E2=80=9D so i=
ts competitors include, like, eating dinner with your friends.)So the quest=
ion is: Does Facebook=E2=80=99s dominant position give it the power to=C2=
=A0unilaterally jack up the price of social networking? The government woul=
d have an easy time proving its case if it could point to examples of where=
 Facebook=C2=A0had=C2=A0jacked up the price of, say, posting baby pictures =
on your timeline. (=E2=80=9CWhere a plaintiff can provide direct proof that=
 a =E2=80=98firm has in fact profitably done so, the existence of monopoly =
power is clear.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D) But of course it can=E2=80=99t, because =
Facebook has never jacked up the price of posting on or looking at Facebook=
 (or Instagram), because a basic feature of modern personal social networki=
ng sites is that they are free and ad-supported.=C2=A0You could imagine an =
alternate theory in which the government argued that Facebook had a monopol=
y in online advertising (implausible), or in, like, =E2=80=9Conline adverti=
sing on social networking sites=E2=80=9D (harder to argue that this is a re=
levant antitrust market), and that it could use that power to jack up the p=
rices it charges advertisers. That is, you might imagine the government arg=
uing that Facebook does or could act like a monopolist toward its paying=C2=
=A0customers (advertisers), rather than toward its non-paying social-networ=
king customers. But the government does not argue those things.Instead it a=
rgues that Facebook has such a dominant share in the personal social networ=
king market that it=C2=A0is=C2=A0a monopolist, which I suppose means that i=
t=C2=A0could=C2=A0raise prices if it wanted to. I don=E2=80=99t think that=
=E2=80=99s a crazy argument; people obviously get a lot of utility out of s=
ocial networking, and that utility largely comes from network effects, and =
if Facebook started charging I am sure a lot of people would just pay its f=
ees rather than try to switch to some other network that their friends aren=
=E2=80=99t on. But the government has not done a very good job of making th=
at argument. The judge writes:Although the Court, as just explained, finds =
the contours of the asserted product market plausible, the Complaint is und=
oubtedly light on specific factual allegations regarding consumer-switching=
 preferences. Given that thin showing, and the fact that the PSN-services p=
roduct market is somewhat =E2=80=9Cidiosyncratically drawn=E2=80=9D to begi=
n with, the Court must demand something more robust from Plaintiff=E2=80=99=
s market-share allegations. As it happens, however, those allegations are e=
ven more tentative: the FTC alleges only that Facebook has =E2=80=9Cmaintai=
ned a dominant share of the U.S. personal social networking market (in exce=
ss of 60%)=E2=80=9D since 2011,=C2=A0 and that =E2=80=9Cno other social net=
work of comparable scale exists in the United States.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0That is=
 it. These allegations =E2=80=94 which do not even provide an estimated act=
ual figure or range for Facebook=E2=80=99s market share at any point over t=
he past ten years =E2=80=94 ultimately fall short of plausibly establishing=
 that Facebook holds market power.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6Even accepting that merely=
 alleging market share =E2=80=9Cin excess of 60%=E2=80=9D might sometimes b=
e acceptable, it cannot suffice in this context, where Plaintiff does not e=
ven allege what it is measuring. Indeed, in its Opposition the FTC expressl=
y contends that it need not =E2=80=9Cspecify which=C2=A0. . . metrics . . .=
 [or] =E2=80=98method=E2=80=99 [it] used to calculate Facebook=E2=80=99s [m=
arket] share.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0 In a case involving a more typical goods marke=
t, perhaps the Court might be able to reasonably infer how Plaintiff arrive=
d at its calculations =E2=80=94 e.g., by proportion of total revenue or of =
units sold. As the above market-definition analysis underscores, however, t=
he market at issue here is unusual in a number of ways, including that the =
products therein are not sold for a price, meaning that PSN services earn n=
o direct revenue from users. The Court is thus unable to understand exactly=
 what the agency=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9C60%-plus=E2=80=9D figure is even referr=
ing to, let alone able to infer the underlying facts that might substantiat=
e it.=C2=A0He concludes:The Court=E2=80=99s decision here does not rest on =
some pleading technicality or arcane feature of antitrust law. Rather, the =
existence of market power is at the heart of any monopolization claim. As t=
he Supreme Court explained in Twombly, itself an antitrust case, =E2=80=9C[=
A] district court must retain the power to insist upon some specificity in =
pleading before allowing a potentially massive factual controversy to proce=
ed.=E2=80=9D Here, this Court must exercise that power. The FTC=E2=80=99s C=
omplaint says almost nothing concrete on the key question of how much power=
 Facebook actually had, and still has, in a properly defined antitrust prod=
uct market. It is almost as if the agency expects the Court to simply nod t=
o the conventional wisdom that Facebook is a monopolist. After all, no one =
who hears the title of the 2010 film =E2=80=9CThe Social Network=E2=80=9D w=
onders which company it is about. Yet, whatever it may mean to the public, =
=E2=80=9Cmonopoly power=E2=80=9D is a term of art under federal law with a =
precise economic meaning: the=C2=A0power to profitably raise prices or excl=
ude competition in a properly defined market. To merely allege that a defen=
dant firm has somewhere over 60% share of an unusual, nonintuitive product =
market =E2=80=94 the confines of which are only somewhat fleshed out and th=
e players within which remain almost entirely unspecified =E2=80=94 is not =
enough. The FTC has therefore fallen short of its pleading burden.That said=
, the government=E2=80=99s position is=C2=A0not=C2=A0crazy, it=E2=80=99s ju=
st not fleshed out, so the judge dismissed the complaint but suggested that=
 the FTC should try again with a bit more specificity.[2] Perhaps the FTC w=
ill re-file a complaint making clearer arguments that Facebook has market p=
ower, and then it can move on to debate whether Facebook abused that power =
by, for instance, excluding competitors.[3] Here at Bloomberg Opinion,  Tae=
 Kim writes=C2=A0that =E2=80=9Cit shouldn=E2=80=99t be difficult for the ag=
ency to come up with the required backup,=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9Cit=E2=
=80=99s also likely any renewed legal action will be formidable.=E2=80=9DBu=
t in some ways the most important sentence in the opinion is: =E2=80=9CIt i=
s almost as if the agency expects the Court to simply nod to the convention=
al wisdom that Facebook is a monopolist.=E2=80=9D It seems totally plausibl=
e that:=09Facebook might not have a monopoly in social networking in the tr=
aditional antitrust sense, in that it cannot unilaterally raise prices (fro=
m zero) for posting baby pictures online,[4] but=09Facebook definitely has =
a monopoly in social networking in some colloquial but important sense, in =
that a ton of people spend a ton of time on Facebook products (Facebook, In=
stagram, WhatsApp) and that gives Facebook enormous political and social an=
d economic power, and some government regulator of corporate bigness =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0some antitrust regulator =E2=80=94=C2=A0should have the ability to=
 police that power.It is striking that one immediate widespread reaction to=
 the Facebook ruling is that, if Facebook isn=E2=80=99t against the law,=C2=
=A0we need to change the law. From the Wall Street Journal:University of Pe=
nnsylvania law professor Herbert Hovenkamp said while the FTC likely has wa=
ys it could amend its allegations to at least get its case out of the start=
ing gate, Monday=E2=80=99s ruling would almost certainly increase calls in =
Congress to pass new antitrust legislation.=E2=80=9CThis sends a signal tha=
t the antitrust laws are not good enough,=E2=80=9D Mr. Hovenkamp said of th=
e rulings. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s going to pour pretty cold water on the ide=
a that the existing antitrust laws can do the job.=E2=80=9D Bloomberg:=E2=
=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not hard to look at these cases and come away with the s=
ense that antitrust law, as it stands, is not capable of handling the probl=
ems posed by dominant technology companies,=E2=80=9D said Blake Reid, a pro=
fessor at the University of Colorado Law School.The New York Times:=E2=80=
=9CToday=E2=80=99s development in the F.T.C.=E2=80=99s case against Faceboo=
k shows that antitrust reform is urgently needed,=E2=80=9D said Representat=
ive Ken Buck, a Republican from Colorado and a co-sponsor of the antitrust =
bills. =E2=80=9CCongress needs to provide additional tools and resources to=
 our antitrust enforcers to go after Big Tech companies engaging in anticom=
petitive conduct.=E2=80=9DDealbook:The ruling is a blow to the antitrust mo=
vement that is gaining momentum in Washington. The biggest takeaway from th=
e case is this: The monopoly case against one of Big Tech=E2=80=99s key pla=
yers is out of step with the law as currently written. What needs to be est=
ablished is whether what Facebook is doing, as defined by the law and rulin=
gs in other cases, is illegal. The answer seems to be no.The judge=E2=80=99=
s ruling also added evidence for those who say the law is not up to the tas=
k of keeping Big Tech in check.=C2=A0The theory is that dominant trillion-d=
ollar tech companies might be bad even if they don=E2=80=99t =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0even if they=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0raise prices for con=
sumers, that giant companies can have social and political and economic pow=
er that is not captured by standard U.S. antitrust law=E2=80=99s focus on c=
onsumer welfare. This theory is sometimes called=C2=A0=E2=80=9Chipster anti=
trust,=E2=80=9D and its leading proponent is probably Lina Khan, who was sw=
orn in as=C2=A0the chair of the FTC as of two weeks ago. I think Khan=E2=80=
=99s FTC=C2=A0does=C2=A0kind of want=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe Court to simply nod =
to the conventional wisdom that Facebook is a monopolist=E2=80=9D; I think =
that a lot of people, including Khan, think=C2=A0that that conventional wis=
dom captures something important, and that if our current antitrust law dis=
agrees then the law is wrong.A tech business modelBack in the day, we used =
to talk about the =E2=80=9CMoviePass economy,=E2=80=9D the idea that a lot =
of startups were in the business of showing rapid user growth by using vent=
ure capitalists=E2=80=99 money to subsidize consumers. The schematic model =
was:=09Raise a million dollars from friends and family.=09Set up an app who=
se only function was giving people $10 for signing up.=09A hundred people s=
ign up the first month, word of the app gets out, and=C2=A099,900 sign up t=
he second month.=09You have a large and enthusiastic user base with=C2=A0a =
huge growth rate, things that venture capitalists love.=09Raise another $1 =
billion from VCS at an enormous valuation, cashing out a few hundred millio=
n dollars for the founders.=09Step 6 is a mystery.Obviously in practice it =
rarely worked exactly=C2=A0this way; the trade was not =E2=80=9Cliterally h=
and out $10 to customers=E2=80=9D but =E2=80=9Csell customers desirable goo=
ds or services for well below cost, subsidized by VC money.=E2=80=9D And ob=
viously the VCs would not describe it quite this way; they would say that y=
ou are seeking user growth to achieve scale, and once you achieve that scal=
e your unit costs will drop and you=E2=80=99ll become profitable.This econo=
my is not what it used to be, for various reasons (the companies failed or =
went public, they started raising prices to economic levels, etc.). But the=
 principle is good. If you are a tech company and someone will just hand yo=
u billions of dollars to pass along to users, you should be able to achieve=
 rapid growth and a high valuation. =E2=80=9CBut it is not actually easy to=
 hand out billions of dollars,=E2=80=9D you might say, =E2=80=9Cit requires=
 good user-interface design and thoughtful attention to=C2=A0customer acqui=
sition, and the U.S. payments system is complicated so you need to build an=
 architecture to interface with banks to make the payments,=E2=80=9D but do=
 you realize how absurd you sound? Yes right the execution of =E2=80=9Cjust=
 hand out billions of dollars=E2=80=9D is complicated, but at its core it i=
s a pretty simple business model. The main trick is finding someone to give=
 you the billions of dollars.Last year the U.S. government decided to hand =
out billions of dollars to businesses, in the form of forgivable government=
-guaranteed loans=C2=A0under the Paycheck Protection Program. This created =
a huge opportunity for tech companies:Two small companies came out of nowhe=
re and, through an astute mix of technology and advertising =E2=80=94 and t=
he dogged pursuit of an opportunity that big banks missed =E2=80=94 found a=
 way to help those businesses. They also helped themselves. For their work,=
 the companies stand to collect more than $3 billion in fees, according to =
a New York Times analysis =E2=80=94 far more than any of the 5,200 particip=
ating lenders.One of the companies, Blueacorn, didn=E2=80=99t exist before =
the pandemic. The other, Womply, founded a decade ago, sold marketing softw=
are. But this year, they became the breakout stars of the Paycheck Protecti=
on Program, the government=E2=80=99s $800 billion relief effort for small b=
usinesses. Between them, the two companies processed a third of all P.P.P. =
loans made this year, the Times analysis found.For small PPP loans (under $=
50,000), the government would pay banks fees of 50% of the loan amount, up =
to a maximum of $2,500. That's pretty good for a loan with no credit risk! =
But lots of banks are not really in the business of hunting down =E2=80=9Cu=
nprofitable solo businesses=E2=80=9D to give them risk-free loans, because =
that is not ordinarily a thing. So Blueacorn and Womply came along and said=
, look, we are tech companies, we can set up a webpage, we can buy ads:=E2=
=80=9CLiterally free money for those who qualify,=E2=80=9D a Blueacorn adve=
rtisement on Facebook read. Womply banners adorned billboards and New York =
City buses. =E2=80=9CGet up to $50,000 in PPP,=E2=80=9D read one. =E2=80=9C=
Apply now!=E2=80=9DAnd by literally advertising literally free money, they =
were able to sign up a bunch of customers, which (1) you might think would =
be easy but (2) was apparently hard enough that no one else did it. And the=
n they partnered with banks to get PPP loans for the customers, and they to=
ok vast chunks of the banks=E2=80=99 fees for themselves, and now their fou=
nders are dynastically wealthy from spending one year shoveling government =
money to small businesses. I hope the founders use their billions to fund l=
ibertarian think tanks and seasteads and cryptocurrency projects. =E2=80=9C=
As self-made tech billionaires,=E2=80=9D they can say, =E2=80=9Cwe understa=
nd the importance of entrepreneurship and cutting through government regula=
tion and red tape, and we are concerned about America=E2=80=99s embrace of =
socialism.=E2=80=9DI want to be clear that I have no problem with any of th=
is. There was a genuine macroeconomic and, frankly, humanitarian problem th=
at the U.S. government really wanted to solve: It wanted to rapidly pump ou=
t billions of dollars to small businesses to keep the economy together duri=
ng the Covid pandemic. Doing this, in turn, required=C2=A0certain loan-admi=
nistration and business-evaluation skills that the government lacks but ban=
ks have, so the government contracted the problem out to banks; it also req=
uired solving certain user-interface and customer-acquisition problems that=
 neither banks nor=C2=A0the government are great at, so=C2=A0they effective=
ly contracted those problems out to some tech companies on a speculative ba=
sis. The tech companies who solved the problems did an important service an=
d=C2=A0got very rich. Still, another way to put it is that the U.S. governm=
ent paid these people $3 billion to set up some websites and buy some bus a=
ds, which feels, with the benefit of hindsight, weird.


