10px;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Facebook</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yesterday a U.S. federal ju=
dge <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24305256.25693=
0/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMjgvZmFjZ=
WJvb2std2lucy1kaXNtaXNzYWwtb2YtdS1zLXN0YXRlcy1tb25vcG9seS1sYXdzdWl0cw/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB95ee9ce9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> dismissed two antitrust lawsuits</a> against Facebook =
Inc., brought by the U.S. Federal Trade Commission and a group of state att=
orneys general,=C2=A0claiming that it has a monopoly on social networking. =
Facebook investors celebrated by buying its stock and pushing its market ca=
pitalization above $1 trillion, which is maybe a little on the nose? =E2=80=
=9CWhat, little old us, a=C2=A0<em>monopoly</em>? No, alas,=C2=A0we=E2=80=
=99re just a=C2=A0scrappy little startup=C2=A0doing our best to survive in =
this crazy world,=E2=80=9D Mark Zuckerberg could say, nervously trying to s=
tand between you and the ticker showing that his company is now worth a tri=
llion dollars. I dunno, doesn=E2=80=99t a trillion dollars=C2=A0<em>sound=
=C2=A0</em>like a monopoly?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s =
the basic problem with the Facebook case. To win an antitrust lawsuit, the =
government has to show that Facebook has =E2=80=9Cmonopoly power=E2=80=9D i=
n some relevant market. Monopoly power means, specifically, the ability to =
raise prices above a competitive level. Here=E2=80=99s how <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24305256.256930/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdG9yYW=
dlLmNvdXJ0bGlzdGVuZXIuY29tL3JlY2FwL2dvdi51c2NvdXJ0cy5kY2QuMjI0OTIxL2dvdi51c=
2NvdXJ0cy5kY2QuMjI0OTIxLjczLjAucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB84193f76" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the judge=E2=
=80=99s opinion</a> puts the question[1]:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Monopoly power is the =E2=80=9Cthe power to control prices or ex=
clude competition,=E2=80=9D such that a firm is a monopolist =E2=80=9Cif it=
 can profitably raise prices substantially above the competitive level.=E2=
=80=9D Where a plaintiff can provide direct proof that a =E2=80=9Cfirm has =
in fact profitably done so, the existence of monopoly power is clear.=E2=80=
=9D Because such proof is rare, however, plaintiffs and courts usually sear=
ch for indirect or =E2=80=9Ccircumstantial evidence=E2=80=9D of monopoly po=
wer by inferring it from =E2=80=9Ca firm=E2=80=99s possession of a dominant=
 share of a relevant market.=E2=80=9D Because =E2=80=9C[m]arket power is me=
aningful only if it is durable,=E2=80=9D a plaintiff proceeding by the indi=
rect method of providing a relevant market and share thereof must also show=
 that there are =E2=80=9Cbarriers to entry=E2=80=9D into that market.=C2=A0=
</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fine. Now, what is the releva=
nt market? The government argued, and the court accepted, that the market i=
s =E2=80=9CPersonal Social Networking (PSN) Services.=E2=80=9D I will not b=
other discussing the definition of this market because you probably get the=
 gist of it. (Facebook objected that this is not a well-defined market and =
that =E2=80=9Cit is =E2=80=98obvious that people=E2=80=99 also know how to =
=E2=80=98connect and share with family and friends . . . via many [other] t=
echnologies,=E2=80=99 such as =E2=80=98email, messaging, photo-sharing, and=
 video-chats,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D but never mind. Facebook has <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24305256.256930/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDctMzAva29kYWstaXMtcmVsZXZ=
hbnQtYWdhaW4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd68da529" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> previously argued</a> that it is not=
 a monopoly because it competes in =E2=80=9Cthe space of people connecting =
with other people,=E2=80=9D so its competitors include, like, eating dinner=
 with your friends.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the question is: Do=
es Facebook=E2=80=99s dominant position give it the power to=C2=A0unilatera=
lly jack up the price of social networking? The government would have an ea=
sy time proving its case if it could point to examples of where Facebook=C2=
=A0<em>had=C2=A0</em>jacked up the price of, say, posting baby pictures on =
your timeline. (=E2=80=9CWhere a plaintiff can provide direct proof that a =
=E2=80=98firm has in fact profitably done so, the existence of monopoly pow=
er is clear.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D) But of course it can=E2=80=99t, because Fac=
ebook has never jacked up the price of posting on or looking at Facebook (o=
r Instagram), because a basic feature of modern personal social networking =
sites is that they are free and ad-supported.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">You could imagine an alternate theory in which the government argu=
ed that Facebook had a monopoly in online advertising (implausible), or in,=
 like, =E2=80=9Conline advertising on social networking sites=E2=80=9D (har=
der to argue that this is a relevant antitrust market), and that it could u=
se that power to jack up the prices it charges advertisers. That is, you mi=
ght imagine the government arguing that Facebook does or could act like a m=
onopolist toward its <em>paying=C2=A0</em>customers (advertisers), rather t=
han toward its non-paying social-networking customers. But the government d=
oes not argue those things.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead it argu=
es that Facebook has such a dominant share in the personal social networkin=
g market that it=C2=A0<em>is</em>=C2=A0a monopolist, which I suppose means =
that it=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>raise prices if it wanted to. I don=E2=80=
=99t think that=E2=80=99s a crazy argument; people obviously get a lot of u=
tility out of social networking, and that utility largely comes from networ=
k effects, and if Facebook started charging I am sure a lot of people would=
 just pay its fees rather than try to switch to some other network that the=
ir friends aren=E2=80=99t on. But the government has not done a very good j=
ob of making that argument. The judge writes:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Although the Court, as just explained, finds the contours of=
 the asserted product market plausible, the Complaint is undoubtedly light =
on specific factual allegations regarding consumer-switching preferences. G=
iven that thin showing, and the fact that the PSN-services product market i=
s somewhat =E2=80=9Cidiosyncratically drawn=E2=80=9D to begin with, the Cou=
rt must demand something more robust from Plaintiff=E2=80=99s market-share =
allegations. As it happens, however, those allegations are even more tentat=
ive: the FTC alleges only that Facebook has =E2=80=9Cmaintained a dominant =
share of the U.S. personal social networking market (in excess of 60%)=E2=
=80=9D since 2011,=C2=A0 and that =E2=80=9Cno other social network of compa=
rable scale exists in the United States.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0That is it. These al=
legations =E2=80=94 which do not even provide an estimated actual figure or=
 range for Facebook=E2=80=99s market share at any point over the past ten y=
ears =E2=80=94 ultimately fall short of plausibly establishing that Faceboo=
k holds market power.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Even a=
ccepting that merely alleging market share =E2=80=9Cin excess of 60%=E2=80=
=9D might sometimes be acceptable, it cannot suffice in this context, where=
 Plaintiff does not even allege what it is measuring. Indeed, in its Opposi=
tion the FTC expressly contends that it need not =E2=80=9Cspecify which=C2=
=A0. . . metrics . . . [or] =E2=80=98method=E2=80=99 [it] used to calculate=
 Facebook=E2=80=99s [market] share.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0 In a case involving a mo=
re typical goods market, perhaps the Court might be able to reasonably infe=
r how Plaintiff arrived at its calculations =E2=80=94 e.g., by proportion o=
f total revenue or of units sold. As the above market-definition analysis u=
nderscores, however, the market at issue here is unusual in a number of way=
s, including that the products therein are not sold for a price, meaning th=
at PSN services earn no direct revenue from users. The Court is thus unable=
 to understand exactly what the agency=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9C60%-plus=E2=80=9D=
 figure is even referring to, let alone able to infer the underlying facts =
that might substantiate it.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">He concludes:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Court=E2=
=80=99s decision here does not rest on some pleading technicality or arcane=
 feature of antitrust law. Rather, the existence of market power is at the =
heart of any monopolization claim. As the Supreme Court explained in Twombl=
y, itself an antitrust case, =E2=80=9C[A] district court must retain the po=
wer to insist upon some specificity in pleading before allowing a potential=
ly massive factual controversy to proceed.=E2=80=9D Here, this Court must e=
xercise that power. The FTC=E2=80=99s Complaint says almost nothing concret=
e on the key question of how much power Facebook actually had, and still ha=
s, in a properly defined antitrust product market. It is almost as if the a=
gency expects the Court to simply nod to the conventional wisdom that Faceb=
ook is a monopolist. After all, no one who hears the title of the 2010 film=
 =E2=80=9CThe Social Network=E2=80=9D wonders which company it is about. Ye=
t, whatever it may mean to the public, =E2=80=9Cmonopoly power=E2=80=9D is =
a term of art under federal law with a precise economic meaning: the=C2=A0p=
ower to profitably raise prices or exclude competition in a properly define=
d market. To merely allege that a defendant firm has somewhere over 60% sha=
re of an unusual, nonintuitive product market =E2=80=94 the confines of whi=
ch are only somewhat fleshed out and the players within which remain almost=
 entirely unspecified =E2=80=94 is not enough. The FTC has therefore fallen=
 short of its pleading burden.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>That said, the government=E2=80=99s position is=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>cra=
zy, it=E2=80=99s just not fleshed out, so the judge dismissed the complaint=
 but suggested that the FTC should try again with a bit more specificity.[2=
] Perhaps the FTC will re-file a complaint making clearer arguments that Fa=
cebook has market power, and then it can move on to debate whether Facebook=
 abused that power by, for instance, excluding competitors.[3] Here at Bloo=
mberg Opinion, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/243=
05256.256930/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMj=
EtMDYtMjgvZmFjZWJvb2stcy1jbGltYi10by0xLXRyaWxsaW9uLW5lZWRzLWFuLWFzdGVyaXNr/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB31e1f90c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;"> Tae Kim writes</a>=C2=A0that =E2=80=9Cit shouldn=
=E2=80=99t be difficult for the agency to come up with the required backup,=
=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s also likely any renewed legal acti=
on will be formidable.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in some=
 ways the most important sentence in the opinion is: =E2=80=9CIt is almost =
as if the agency expects the Court to simply nod to the conventional wisdom=
 that Facebook is a monopolist.=E2=80=9D It seems totally plausible that:</=
p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0=
;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Facebook might not have a monopoly =
in social networking in the traditional antitrust sense, in that it cannot =
unilaterally raise prices (from zero) for posting baby pictures online,[4] =
but</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Facebook definitely has a mono=
poly in social networking in some colloquial but important sense, in that a=
 ton of people spend a ton of time on Facebook products (Facebook, Instagra=
m, WhatsApp) and that gives Facebook enormous political and social and econ=
omic power, and some government regulator of corporate bigness =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0some antitrust regulator =E2=80=94=C2=A0should have the ability to polic=
e that power.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is striking that one=
 immediate widespread reaction to the Facebook ruling is that, if Facebook =
isn=E2=80=99t against the law,=C2=A0we need to change the law. From <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24305256.256930/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9mZWRlcmFsLWp1ZGdlLWRpc21pc3Nlcy1nb3Zlcm5tZW50=
LWFudGl0cnVzdC1sYXdzdWl0cy1hZ2FpbnN0LWZhY2Vib29rLTExNjI0OTA3NzQ3P21vZD1ocF9=
sZWFkX3BvczQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB10b47c34" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the Wall Street Journal</a>:</p><bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">University of Pennsylvania law professo=
r Herbert Hovenkamp said while the FTC likely has ways it could amend its a=
llegations to at least get its case out of the starting gate, Monday=E2=80=
=99s ruling would almost certainly increase calls in Congress to pass new a=
ntitrust legislation.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis sends a=
 signal that the antitrust laws are not good enough,=E2=80=9D Mr. Hovenkamp=
 said of the rulings. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s going to pour pretty cold water=
 on the idea that the existing antitrust laws can do the job.=E2=80=9D</p><=
/blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/24305256.256930/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9u=
ZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMjkvc2F2aW5nLWZhY2Vib29rLWNhc2UtZmFsbHMtdG8tdGV=
jaC1mb2Uta2hhbi1pbi1maXJzdC10ZXN0LWF0LWZ0Yw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2cc173=
2c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Bloom=
berg</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s=
 not hard to look at these cases and come away with the sense that antitrus=
t law, as it stands, is not capable of handling the problems posed by domin=
ant technology companies,=E2=80=9D said Blake Reid, a professor at the Univ=
ersity of Colorado Law School.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24305256.2569=
30/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMS8wNi8yOC90ZWNobm9sb2d5L2ZhY2Vib29r=
LWZ0Yy1sYXdzdWl0Lmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6a38c22c" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">New York Times</a>:</p><bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CToday=E2=80=99s development =
in the F.T.C.=E2=80=99s case against Facebook shows that antitrust reform i=
s urgently needed,=E2=80=9D said Representative Ken Buck, a Republican from=
 Colorado and a co-sponsor of the antitrust bills. =E2=80=9CCongress needs =
to provide additional tools and resources to our antitrust enforcers to go =
after Big Tech companies engaging in anticompetitive conduct.=E2=80=9D</p><=
/blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/24305256.256930/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAy=
MS8wNi8yOS9idXNpbmVzcy9kZWFsYm9vay9mYWNlYm9vay1hbnRpdHJ1c3QtZnRjLmh0bWw/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa77b59f9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">Dealbook</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">The ruling is a blow to the antitrust movement that is gaining momentu=
m in Washington. The biggest takeaway from the case is this: The monopoly c=
ase against one of Big Tech=E2=80=99s key players is out of step with the l=
aw as currently written. What needs to be established is whether what Faceb=
ook is doing, as defined by the law and rulings in other cases, is illegal.=
 The answer seems to be no.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The judge=E2=80=
=99s ruling also added evidence for those who say the law is not up to the =
task of keeping Big Tech in check.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">The theory is that dominant trillion-dollar tech companies might=
 be bad even if they don=E2=80=99t =E2=80=94=C2=A0even if they=C2=A0<em>can=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0raise prices for consumers, that giant =
companies can have social and political and economic power that is not capt=
ured by standard U.S. antitrust law=E2=80=99s focus on consumer welfare. Th=
is theory is sometimes called=C2=A0=E2=80=9Chipster antitrust,=E2=80=9D and=
 its leading proponent is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/24305256.256930/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYXRsYW50aWMuY29tL21hZ2F6aW5lL2F=
yY2hpdmUvMjAxOC8wNy9saW5hLWtoYW4tYW50aXRydXN0LzU2MTc0My8/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB039375c7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">probably Lina Khan</a>, who <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/24305256.256930/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnRjLmdvdi9hYm91dC1mdGMvYm=
lvZ3JhcGhpZXMvbGluYS1raGFu/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3621298c" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
