e" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">a huge opportunity for tech companies</a>:</p><blockqu=
ote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two small companies came out of nowhere an=
d, through an astute mix of technology and advertising =E2=80=94 and the do=
gged pursuit of an opportunity that big banks missed =E2=80=94 found a way =
to help those businesses. They also helped themselves. For their work, the =
companies stand to collect more than $3 billion in fees, according to a New=
 York Times analysis =E2=80=94 far more than any of the 5,200 participating=
 lenders.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One of the companies, Blueacorn, =
didn=E2=80=99t exist before the pandemic. The other, Womply, founded a deca=
de ago, sold marketing software. But this year, they became the breakout st=
ars of the Paycheck Protection Program, the government=E2=80=99s $800 billi=
on relief effort for small businesses. Between them, the two companies proc=
essed a third of all P.P.P. loans made this year, the Times analysis found.=
</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For small PPP loans (under $5=
0,000), the government would pay banks fees of 50% of the loan amount, up t=
o a maximum of $2,500. That's pretty good for a loan with no credit risk! B=
ut lots of banks are not really in the business of hunting down =E2=80=9Cun=
profitable solo businesses=E2=80=9D to give them risk-free loans, because t=
hat is not ordinarily a thing. So Blueacorn and Womply came along and said,=
 look, we are tech companies, we can set up a webpage, we can buy ads:</p><=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CLiterally free money for t=
hose who qualify,=E2=80=9D a Blueacorn advertisement on Facebook read. Womp=
ly banners adorned billboards and New York City buses. =E2=80=9CGet up to $=
50,000 in PPP,=E2=80=9D read one. =E2=80=9CApply now!=E2=80=9D</p></blockqu=
ote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And by literally advertising literally fre=
e money, they were able to sign up a bunch of customers, which (1) you migh=
t think would be easy but (2) was apparently hard enough that no one else d=
id it. And then they partnered with banks to get PPP loans for the customer=
s, and they took vast chunks of the banks=E2=80=99 fees for themselves, and=
 now their founders are dynastically wealthy from spending one year shoveli=
ng government money to small businesses. I hope the founders use their bill=
ions to fund libertarian think tanks and seasteads and cryptocurrency proje=
cts. =E2=80=9CAs self-made tech billionaires,=E2=80=9D they can say, =E2=80=
=9Cwe understand the importance of entrepreneurship and cutting through gov=
ernment regulation and red tape, and we are concerned about America=E2=80=
=99s embrace of socialism.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I want =
to be clear that I have no problem with any of this. There was a genuine ma=
croeconomic and, frankly, humanitarian problem that the U.S. government rea=
lly wanted to solve: It wanted to rapidly pump out billions of dollars to s=
mall businesses to keep the economy together during the Covid pandemic. Doi=
ng this, in turn, required=C2=A0certain loan-administration and business-ev=
aluation skills that the government lacks but banks have, so the government=
 contracted the problem out to banks; it also required solving certain user=
-interface and customer-acquisition problems that neither banks nor=C2=A0th=
e government are great at, so=C2=A0they effectively contracted those proble=
ms out to some tech companies on a speculative basis. The tech companies wh=
o solved the problems did an important service and=C2=A0got very rich. Stil=
l, another way to put it is that the U.S. government paid these people $3 b=
illion to set up some websites and buy some bus ads, which feels, with the =
benefit of hindsight, weird.</p>
